I've read both files. Here's the full audit.

---

## Test Anti-Pattern Audit: `SerializerTests.cs`

**Summary: 5 Critical · 1 High · 2 Medium · 0 Low**

This suite is largely a collection of tautological assertions. Most tests assert `output == input` on operations where the input was chosen to be a fixed point of the transformation, so the tests pass regardless of whether the production code works.

---

### Critical — Tests Giving False Confidence

**① `UpperCase_ToUpper_Works` (line 73–76) — Self-referential assertion**

Input `"HELLO"` is already uppercase. `ToUpper()` is a no-op on it, so `Assert.AreEqual(input, result)` is always true. A broken `ToUpper` still passes.

```csharp
// Before — tautological: input is already uppercase
var input = "HELLO";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual(input, result);

// Fix — use a mixed-case input so the transformation is observable
var input = "hello";
var result = input.ToUpper();
Assert.AreEqual("HELLO", result);
```

**② `NormalizeName_AlreadyNormalized_NoChange` (line 37–41) — Self-referential assertion**

`"alice"` is already trimmed and lowercase — exactly what `Normalize` returns for normalized input. This is the only test for `Normalize`, yet it never verifies the transformation. If `Normalize` were `return name;` (a no-op), this test still passes.

```csharp
// Before — input is already a fixed point of Normalize
var name = "alice";
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize(name);
Assert.AreEqual(name, result);

// Fix — use input that actually requires transformation
var result = NameNormalizer.Normalize("  ALICE  ");
Assert.AreEqual("alice", result);
```

**③ `GetDisplayName_ReturnsFormattedName` (line 55–60) — Self-referential assertion**

The expected value is derived from the SUT's own input field. `GetDisplayName()` currently returns `Name` verbatim, so `Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display)` is `Assert.AreEqual(x, x)`. If someone adds real formatting (e.g., `"Alice (age 30)"`), this test still passes with the old no-op implementation.

```csharp
// Before — expected comes from the SUT input
Assert.AreEqual(user.Name, display);

// Fix — assert against a literal expected value
var user = new UserDto { Name = "Alice", Age = 30 };
var display = user.GetDisplayName();
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", display);  // or "Alice (30)" if formatting is intended
```

**④ `MapToDto_MapBack_RoundTrip` (line 45–53) — Lossy round-trip assertion**

`Mapper.ToDto` drops `Id` and `Email` (sets `Age = 0`). `Mapper.ToEntity` drops `Age` (sets `Id = 0`, `Email = ""`). This is a **lossy** mapping by design. A round-trip test on a lossy transform either: (a) fails because data was lost (`entity.Id = 1` vs `backToEntity.Id = 0`), or (b) hides the loss if you only check the surviving field. Either way, the test concept is wrong. Each direction should be tested independently with hardcoded expected values.

```csharp
// Fix — test each direction independently
[TestMethod]
public void ToDto_MapsFullNameToName()
{
    var entity = new UserEntity { Id = 1, FullName = "Alice Smith", Email = "a@b.com" };
    var dto = Mapper.ToDto(entity);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", dto.Name);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, dto.Age);   // documents that Age is not mapped
}

[TestMethod]
public void ToEntity_MapsNameToFullName()
{
    var dto = new UserDto { Name = "Alice Smith", Age = 30 };
    var entity = Mapper.ToEntity(dto);
    Assert.AreEqual("Alice Smith", entity.FullName);
    Assert.AreEqual(0, entity.Id);      // documents that Id is not mapped
    Assert.AreEqual("", entity.Email);  // documents that Email is not mapped
}
```

**⑤ `Validate_ValidInput_ReturnsSameInput` (line 63–68) — Self-referential assertion / missing rejection tests**

`ValidateEmail` returns its input on success by contract, so `Assert.AreEqual(input, result)` is trivially true. The **actual purpose** of a validator — rejecting bad input — has zero coverage.

```csharp
// Fix — keep the happy path but add the critical rejection case
[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_ValidInput_ReturnsInput()
{
    var result = Validator.ValidateEmail("hello@world.com");
    Assert.AreEqual("hello@world.com", result);
}

[TestMethod]
public void ValidateEmail_MissingAt_Throws()
{
    Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentException>(
        () => Validator.ValidateEmail("invalid"));
}
```

---

### High — Likely to Cause Pain

**⑥ `Clone_ProducesEqualObject` (line 27–34) — Missing reference-inequality assertion**

Asserts field equality but never checks that `clone` is a **different object**. `Clone()` could be `return this;` and this test passes.

```csharp
// Add this assertion
Assert.AreNotSame(original, clone);
```

---

### Medium — Maintainability

| # | Finding | Location | Note |
